      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, you're right! I was so busy thinking about the goblins that I forgot to actually answer your question about the math! That is a *very* common mistake, and it is a goblin error!\n\nYou want the **Nearest Neighbor** heuristic, right? It's the classic \"goblin strategy\" for solving the Traveling Salesman Problem (TSP) without a supercomputer.\n\nHere is how you think about it:\n\nImagine you are a goblin trying to eat all the apples in a forest. You don't have a map of the whole forest, but you have a map of the immediate area. You pick the nearest apple to you, eat it, and then immediately go to the nearest apple to *that* one. You keep doing this until you are back at the start.\n\n**The Logic:**\n1.  **Start at a point** (say, your depot).\n2.  **Pick the closest unvisited point.**\n3.  **Go there.**\n4.  **Repeat** until you are back at the start.\n\n**Why it works (and why it's not perfect):**\nIt works because it minimizes the distance traveled *locally*.",
